                  CHAP. III. The king of China doth arme a fleete of shippes against the rouer Lymahon▪ who withdraweth himselfe to Tonzuacaotican, whereas he hath notice of the Philippinas.
                  THe complayntes increased euerie day more and more vnto the king and his counsell, of the euils doone vnto the Chinos by this rouer Lymahon. For the which commandement was giuen straightwaies vnto the Uiceroy of that prouince (whereas he vsed to execute his euill) that with great expedition he might be taken (for to cut off this inconuenience,One hundred and thirtie great ships of warre with fortie thousand men.) who in few dayes did set foorth to sea, one hundred and thirtie great shippes well appointed, with fortie thousand men in them, and one made generall ouer them all, a gentle man called Omoncon, for to go seeke and fo
